  "prompt": "Which is the best book for learning python for absolute beginners on their own?",
  "response": "For absolute beginners looking to learn Python on their own, here are a few highly recommended books:\n\n1. **\"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\" by Al Sweigart**: This book is great for absolute beginners as it teaches Python programming through practical projects. It covers the basics of Python and shows how to automate everyday tasks, making it engaging and applicable.\n\n2. **\"Python Crash Course\" by Eric Matthes**: This is a hands-on, project-based introduction to Python. The first half of the book covers basic programming concepts, while the second half guides you through building projects, such as games and web applications.\n\n3. **\"Learn Python the Hard Way\" by Zed A. Shaw**: This book takes a more traditional approach to teaching programming. It emphasizes practice and the importance of writing code through exercises. The style can be straightforward, which some learners find beneficial.\n\n4. **\"Head First Python\" by Paul Barry**: This book uses a visually rich format designed to engage readers actively. It covers the fundamentals in a friendly manner and includes exercises at the end of each chapter.\n\n5. **\"Python for Everybody\" by Charles Severance**: This book is oriented towards people without a programming background. It introduces Python programming through a series of practical examples, focusing on data handling and web scraping.\n\nEach of these books has a different style, so you might want to look at a sample chapter or two to see which one resonates with you the most. Ultimately, the best choice will depend on your learning style and preferences!",
